The question itself was wrong!

*_<i><b>Mu*_ ([Japanese](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Japanese_language)/[Korean](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Korean_language)), and _*Wu*_ ([Chinese](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chinese_language) traditional: [無](http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E7%84%A1), simplified: [无](http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E6%97%A0) [pinyin](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pinyin): _wú_ [Jyutping](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jyutping): _mou2_), is a word which has been roughly translated as “no”, “none”, “null”, “without”, and “no meaning”.
The best-known _mu_ koan is as follows: A monk asked [Zhaozhou Congshen](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zhaozhou_Congshen), a Chinese Zen master (known as _Jōshū_ in Japanese), "Has a dog [Buddha-nature](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buddha-nature) or not?" Zhaozhou answered, _"Wú"_ (in Japanese, _Mu_).

<span style="color: #999; font-size: 85%;">— [Mu (negative)](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mu_%28negative%29), [Wikipedia](http://en.wikipedia.org/)</span></blockquote>

Вах! Какое оружие в устах толерантного ритора!